tools_called.args:
{"query": "How does managing semi-natural open habitats with rough grazing compare to using prescribed fire for butterfly and moth populations?", "summary": "Semi-natural habitat management with rough grazing shows primarily positive effects on butterfly and moth populations. Light sheep grazing on saltmarsh for 15-18 years increased species richness of micro-moths compared to moderately or heavily grazed marsh, while also increasing total abundance of micro-moths compared to ungrazed marsh (action 3944). Cattle or pony grazing on calcareous coastal dunes for 4-13 years maintained similar species richness of butterflies compared to unmanaged land or areas managed by cutting, while also increasing abundance of four out of 13 butterfly species and improving site occupancy by brown argus and Alcon large blue butterflies (action 3944). Upland rough grassland managed by livestock grazing had greater species richness and higher abundance of butterflies than improved grassland (action 3944).

Prescribed fire management shows more variable effects on butterfly and moth populations. Four out of nine studies found that burning increased abundance of certain species including heath fritillary adults, marsh fritillary caterpillar webs, and Fender's blue caterpillars and eggs on heathland, fen meadows and prairies, while three studies found decreased abundance of other species including Brenton blue butterfly, rosy marsh moth caterpillars and regal fritillary adults (action 3882). Burning typically had neutral effects on species richness, with prairies and grasslands showing similar richness compared to unburned areas (action 3882). A European review found occasional burning benefitted 10 out of 67 butterfly species of conservation concern (action 3882).

Rotational burning provided more consistent benefits than single burns, with prairies burned more than one to four years ago showing higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than recently burned areas (action 3883). Similarly, rotational grazing showed advantages over continuous grazing, with rotationally grazed grasslands having greater species richness and higher abundance of butterflies and burnet moths than continuously grazed areas (action 3965). Leaving unburned patches during prescribed burning increased abundance of six out of nine specialist butterfly species compared to sites without unburned areas (action 3879).", "action_ids": ["3944","3882","3883","3965","3879"]}

