{
  "query": "What are the benefits for butterflies of maintaining species-rich, semi-natural grasslands compared to using set-aside in European agricultural landscapes?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, species-rich, semi-natural grasslands and set-aside areas both provide benefits for butterflies compared to conventional agricultural land, but with some important differences:\n\nFor species-rich, semi-natural grasslands: Action 133 found that restoring species-rich grassland resulted in higher pollinating insect density and diversity than other types of grassland. Action 3955 showed that semi-natural grasslands restored by scrub clearance and grazing had similar species richness of butterflies and burnet moths to both unrestored and continuously managed grassland in some cases, though one study found lower species richness compared to continuously managed grasslands. Action 3929 demonstrated that grasslands established by sowing grasses, legumes and other broadleaved plants had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than grasslands established with grass-only mixes.\n\nFor set-aside areas: Action 3980 found that sown or naturally regenerating set-aside had greater species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than cereal fields or pasture, especially when sown with less competitive grasses. The same action showed that butterfly abundance in sown set-aside was higher than in cereal fields, particularly when sown with less competitive grasses. Additionally, butterfly communities in older set-aside fields included species which were less migratory, spent longer as caterpillars, and had fewer generations per year than species found in newer set-aside fields.\n\nBoth habitat types showed benefits over conventional farmland, with set-aside particularly effective when managed with appropriate plant species composition and grasslands showing enhanced benefits when established with diverse plant communities including forbs and legumes rather than grass-only mixes.",
  "action_ids": [
    "133",
    "3980",
    "3955",
    "3929"
  ]
}

