{
  "query": "For butterfly conservation in European farmland, how do wildflower strips compare to uncultivated or grass margins?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on European farmland studies, wildflower strips consistently outperform both uncultivated and grass margins for butterfly conservation. Action 3932 shows that field margins sown with wildflowers had greater species richness and abundance of butterflies than grass-only field margins in studies from the UK and Sweden. Similarly, wildflower strips had higher butterfly abundance than uncultivated margins, cropped fields and conventional grassland in studies from the UK, Switzerland and Finland.\n\nWhen comparing uncultivated margins to grass margins, studies show mixed results but generally favor sown options. Action 3981 reports that uncultivated margins had lower species richness and abundance of butterflies than margins sown with grasses and non-woody broadleaved plants (forbs) or wildflowers in studies from Sweden, the UK and Finland. However, action 3982 indicates that floristically enhanced grass buffers or wildflower strips had greater species richness and higher abundance of butterflies than standard grass margins in studies from the UK and Sweden.\n\nThe effectiveness of grass margins varies by their enhancement level - action 3982 shows that grass margins sown with legumes or clover and grass ley had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies and moths than uncultivated margins in Swedish studies. However, action 3981 demonstrates that uncultivated margins which were not cut or only cut in spring/autumn had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than margins cut in summer in UK and German studies.\n\nOverall, the European evidence indicates a clear hierarchy for butterfly conservation: wildflower/nectar flower strips perform best, followed by enhanced grass margins with legumes or wildflowers, then standard grass margins, with uncultivated margins generally performing least well, though management timing can improve uncultivated margin effectiveness.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3932",
    "3981",
    "3982",
    "63"
  ]
}

