{
  "query": "What are the effects of removing or excluding problematic plant and animal species on butterfly and moth populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, removing or excluding problematic plant and animal species has several positive effects on butterfly and moth populations:\n\nRemoving or controlling non-native or problematic plants generally increases butterfly and moth populations. Two studies found that sites where invasive plants were removed by weeding or cutting and applying herbicide had greater species richness of butterflies than untreated sites (Action 3890). Four of six studies found that sites where trees and shrubs were removed or invasive plants were cut had greater abundance of Apollo butterflies, higher density of Fender's blue eggs, or higher total abundance of butterflies compared to untreated sites (Action 3890). Two studies found that sites where invasive plants were removed were used more by Fender's blue and frosted elfin butterflies than untreated sites (Action 3890). Additionally, removal of invasive plants allowed adults from two previously separated populations of Apollo butterflies to mix (Action 3890).\n\nExcluding vertebrate herbivores also benefits butterfly and moth populations. Two of four studies found that forest plots fenced to exclude non-native pigs and deer had greater species richness of butterflies and macro-moths than unfenced plots (Action 3891). Five of eight studies found that plots fenced to exclude deer, sheep, pigs and large herbivores had higher abundance of butterflies, moths, caterpillars, rare macro-moths and New Forest burnet moths than unfenced plots (Action 3891). A global systematic review found that reducing or removing grazing or browsing by wild or domestic herbivores in temperate and boreal forests increased the abundance of butterflies and moths (Action 3891). One study found that all Glanville fritillary caterpillar nests survived in grassland fenced to exclude sheep, compared to 88% in a grazed area (Action 3891).\n\nExcluding invertebrate herbivores shows similar benefits, with one study finding higher density of pearl-bordered fritillary butterflies at sites fenced to exclude grazing animals than at unfenced sites (Action 3885).\n\nExcluding native predators has mixed results for butterfly and moth survival. Three of five studies found that using mesh cages, net sleeves and sticky resin to exclude predators including birds, mammals, spiders and ants increased survival of large copper caterpillars, Boisduval silkworm eggs and caterpillars, and Appalachian brown eggs and juveniles, while two studies found no increase in monarch caterpillar survival (Action 3889).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3890",
    "3891",
    "3885",
    "3889"
  ]
}

