{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effects of restoring post-industrial sites, like mines or brownfields, on butterfly and moth communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Four studies evaluated the effects on butterflies and moths of restoring or creating new habitats after mining and quarrying, with two studies in the Czech Republic, one in the UK, and one in New Zealand (action 3862). One replicated, paired, site comparison study in the Czech Republic found that 15% of 380 invertebrate species (including 208 moth species) were only found on flattened spoil heaps, compared to 30% which were only found on unflattened heaps (action 3862). One replicated, paired, site comparison study in the Czech Republic found that technically restored quarries had a lower species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than quarries left to restore naturally (action 3862). One replicated, paired, site comparison study in the Czech Republic found that flattened spoil heaps had a lower species richness of moths than unflattened spoil heaps (action 3862). One replicated, randomized, controlled study in the UK found that on slate waste tips trees where fertilizer was applied had a similar abundance of caterpillars to trees that were unfertilized (action 3862). One site comparison study in New Zealand found that a peat bog restored after mining supported a similar density of Fred the thread moth caterpillars to undisturbed bogs and caterpillars of a similar size to caterpillars on undisturbed bogs (action 3862). For brownfield or ex-industrial sites specifically, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of protecting or restoring these sites on butterflies and moths (action 3835).",
