{
  "query": "To benefit butterflies on productive grasslands, how does reducing livestock density compare with seasonal livestock removal or reducing mowing frequency?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies of butterfly conservation on grasslands, the three management strategies show different levels of effectiveness:\n\nReducing livestock density shows strong positive effects for butterflies. Five of eight studies found that grasslands grazed with lower stocking densities had greater species richness of adult butterflies, moths, and burnet moths than grassland grazed at higher stocking densities (Action 3959). Eight studies found that grasslands grazed with lower stocking densities had greater abundance of all butterflies, butterflies with grass host plants, moths, burnet moths, their caterpillars, or specific species than grasslands grazed at higher stocking densities (Action 3959). A European review reported that reducing grazing intensity benefitted 41 out of 67 butterfly species of conservation concern (Action 3959).\n\nSeasonal livestock removal shows mixed results. Two of three studies found that grasslands where cattle were removed had similar species richness of butterflies to grasslands grazed throughout the growing season, while one study found greater species richness with summer cattle removal (Action 3960). Three studies found that grasslands where livestock were removed seasonally had higher abundance of butterflies and caterpillars than grasslands grazed continuously, but three other studies found similar abundance between seasonal removal and continuous grazing (Action 3960).\n\nReducing mowing frequency demonstrates positive but variable effects. Two of three studies found that meadows cut once per year had higher species richness of butterflies and moths than meadows cut two or more times per year, while one study found similar species richness regardless of cutting frequency (Action 3961). Three of five studies found that meadows cut once per year had similar abundance of butterflies to meadows cut multiple times per year, while two studies found higher abundance with reduced cutting frequency (Action 3961).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3959",
    "3960",
    "3961"
  ]
}

