{
  "query": "What are the benefits of planting new hedges and managing existing ones for butterfly and moth conservation on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, planting new hedges and managing existing hedgerows provides several benefits for butterfly and moth conservation on farmland. For new hedge planting, established hedgerows had higher species richness of butterflies and macro-moths than in-field beetle banks, crops or pasture (Action 3976). The abundance of butterflies, moths, macro-moths and gatekeepers was higher along hedgerows than on beetle banks, grass margins without hedgerows, in field interiors, or 5-10 metres away from hedgerows (Action 3976). Additionally, gorse, oak and blackthorn planted within hedgerows had more species of arthropods, including caterpillars, than more commonly planted hawthorn (Action 3976). Moths recorded close to hedgerows were more likely to be flying parallel to hedgerows than moths recorded further away (Action 3976). For hedgerow management, hedgerows with trees or more complex structure had higher species richness or diversity of butterflies and macro-moths than simpler hedgerows without trees (Action 3975). Hedgerows cut once every 2-3 years, cut in autumn, or cut to allow incremental growth had higher abundance of adult butterflies and moths, moth caterpillars and pupae, and brown hairstreak eggs than hedgerows cut to the same size every winter (Action 3975). Hedgerows kept between 1-2 m tall had higher species richness of butterflies than hedgerows kept below 1 m tall (Action 3975). Hedgerows managed with scalloped edges or maintained at below 1 m tall had more brown hairstreak eggs and higher abundance of adult butterflies than hedgerows with straight edges or allowed to grow over 2 m tall (Action 3975). Laid or coppiced hedgerows had higher abundance of butterflies than unmanaged hedgerows (Action 3975). Field margins next to hedgerow trees had higher abundance of most shrub- and tree-feeding moth species than margins away from hedgerow trees (Action 3975).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3976",
    "3975"
  ]
}

