{
  "action_id": "562",
  "action_title": "Leave cultivated, uncropped margins or plots (includes 'lapwing plots')",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nNineteen individual studies looked at the effect of uncropped, cultivated margins or plots on wildlife. Seventeen studies from the UK and northwest Europe (six reviews and seven replicated studies of which two were site comparisons, one a before-and-after trial and one was controlled and randomized) found that leaving uncropped, cultivated margins or plots on farmland provides benefits to some or all target farmland bird species, plants, invertebrates, and mammals. These wildlife benefits included increased species richness of plants, bumblebees, species richness and abundance of spiders, abundance of ground-dwelling invertebrates and ground beetles, increased stone curlew breeding population size,\u00a0northern lapwing hatching success, Eurasian skylark nesting success and the establishment, abundance or species richness of rare arable plant species. A replicated study found northern lapwing, Eurasian skylark, grey partridge and yellow wagtail bred in lapwing plots.\nTwo studies (a replicated study and a review) from the UK found that leaving uncropped, cultivated margins or plots on farmland had no effect on 11 out of 12 farmland bird species or ground beetles. A replicated site comparison study in the UK found fewer seed-eating birds on fallow plots for ground-nesting birds in two out of three regions. One review from the UK found evidence that pernicious weeds were more commonly found on uncropped cultivated margins than conservation or conventional headlands. A replicated site comparison from the UK found the proportion of young grey partridges in the population was lower in areas with a high proportion of uncropped cultivated margins and plots."
}

{
  "query": "What are the overall effects on butterfly and moth communities of creating uncropped habitat areas like set-asides and beetle banks within farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies evaluating uncropped habitat areas in farmland, creating set-aside areas generally provides positive effects for butterfly and moth communities. Three of four replicated studies found that sown or naturally regenerating set-aside had greater species richness of butterflies and day-flying moths than cereal fields or pasture, especially when sown with less competitive grasses (Action 3980). Two of five replicated studies found that the abundance of butterflies and day-flying moths in sown set-aside was higher than in cereal fields, particularly when sown with less competitive grasses (Action 3980). Set-aside areas also showed temporal effects, with one study finding higher species richness and abundance of butterflies and day-flying moths in second-year set-aside compared to first-year set-aside (Action 3980).\n\nBeetle banks showed more limited benefits for butterfly and moth communities. One study found that beetle banks and field margins managed under agri-environment schemes had higher species richness of micro-moths and similar species richness of macro-moths compared to conventionally managed field margins (Action 3927). However, beetle banks had lower species richness of butterflies than hedgerows and similar abundance of caterpillars to field margins and crop fields (Action 3927).\n\nUncropped, cultivated margins or plots showed mixed results. Two of three replicated studies found that farms with uncropped cultivated margins had similar species richness of butterflies and moths to conventional farms, while one study found that fields with wider margins between crops had higher butterfly species richness in one of two years (Action 3923). For abundance, one study found farms with uncropped cultivated margins had higher abundance of butterflies and micro-moths but similar abundance of other moths compared to conventionally managed farms (Action 3923).\n\nGrass buffer strips and margins consistently showed positive effects, with studies finding that wider grass margins had greater species richness and diversity of butterflies, macro-moths and micro-moths than narrower margins, and that floristically enhanced grass buffers had greater species richness and abundance of butterflies than standard grass margins (Action 3982).",
