{
  "query": "In European forests, how do the effects of coppicing and clearing patches compare for butterfly and moth communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from 14 studies on clearing patches and 10 studies on coppicing in European forests and other regions:\n\nButterfly Communities: Both management practices generally benefit butterflies compared to unmanaged forests, but with different patterns. Cleared patches in forests had greater species richness of butterflies than coppiced woodland or closed canopy forest (Action 3938). However, coppiced woodland showed variable effects - one study found greater butterfly species richness in coppiced woodland than unmanaged woodland, while another found coppiced woodland had greater species richness than woodland coppiced over 15 years ago (Action 3939). For abundance, cleared patches managed with coppicing and grazing showed higher butterfly abundance than before management or unmanaged areas, with specific benefits for chequered blue, woodland brown, high brown fritillary and small pearl-bordered fritillary (Action 3938). Coppiced woodland also showed higher butterfly abundance than unmanaged woodland, with particular benefits for heath fritillary, and better persistence rates for pearl-bordered and small pearl-bordered fritillaries compared to mature conifer woodland (Action 3939).\n\nMoth Communities: The effects differ markedly between the two practices. Cleared patches in forests had lower species richness of moths than unmanaged patches or coppiced woodland (Action 3938). Additionally, wider rides in cleared areas had lower macro-moth abundance than standard width rides or mature forest (Action 3938). In contrast, coppiced woodland contained more unique macro-moth species than mature forest, though it had lower overall species richness and abundance than mature forest, with no change in abundance related to coppice age (Action 3939). Coppiced woodland of different ages supported different communities of moths and butterflies (Action 3939).\n\nTemporal Effects: Both practices show time-dependent effects. For cleared patches, butterfly species richness and abundance declined over the first three years after clearing, with patches cleared 2-4 years ago having greater heath fritillary abundance than patches cleared 7-11 years ago (Action 3938). For coppicing, the optimal timing appears to be 2-7 years post-coppicing for maximum butterfly abundance, with effectiveness declining after 15 years (Action 3939).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3938",
    "3939"
  ]
}

