{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation and captive-breeding programs?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence for the success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation and captive-breeding programs shows mixed but promising results. For translocation within former range areas, 16 studies found that eight studies reported translocated populations of adult butterflies and Fisher's estuarine moth eggs persisted for 2-12 years and increased in abundance. However, one review across the UK and Ireland found that only 25% of translocated and released captive-bred butterfly populations survived for at least three years, 38% died out in that time, and only 8% were known to have survived for more than 10 years. The review also reported that translocated populations of large copper adults and/or caterpillars survived for up to 38 years but ultimately died out or had to be supplemented by further releases. For translocation outside known range, two of three studies reported that populations of Gillette's checkerspot, small skipper and marbled white persisted and increased in abundance over eight and 28 years respectively. For captive-breeding programs, six studies reported that captive-bred butterfly populations released as eggs, caterpillars, pupae and adults persisted for 2-28 years and increased in abundance. However, two studies reported that captive-bred large copper and belted beauty moth populations died out one, two or 12 years after release, or required further releases to survive. One replicated study found that three of 10 captive-bred barberry carpet moth populations established, and at least one persisted for five years. The same UK and Ireland review found identical survival rates for captive-bred populations as for translocated ones (25% survived >3 years, 8% survived >10 years). Studies also showed that large copper, large white and monarch butterflies were successfully reared in captivity for 12 generations or >25 years, and that survival rates in captivity varied significantly based on rearing conditions including temperature, ant species presence, and host plant species.",
