{
  "query": "How does the scale of habitat features, such as field size and margin width, affect butterfly and moth communities on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies show that the scale of habitat features significantly affects butterfly and moth communities on farmland. Regarding field size, four replicated site comparison studies found that arable and mixed farms and landscapes with smaller fields had a higher abundance of butterflies and burnet moths than areas with larger fields (Action 3974). Two of four studies found that arable farms in more diverse landscapes and landscapes with smaller fields had higher species richness of butterflies and burnet moths than areas with larger fields, while the other two found similar species richness between smaller and larger fields (Action 3974). One before-and-after study found that reducing field size by increasing the length of field edges on a farm, along with increasing meadow and field margin areas, increased the species richness of butterflies and burnet moths (Action 3974).\n\nFor margin width effects, five replicated site comparison studies found that wider grass margins up to 6 meters wide had greater species richness or diversity of butterflies, macro-moths and micro-moths than narrower or conventional width margins, although one study found similar species richness of macro-moths in wide and conventional grass margins (Action 3982). Three of seven replicated site comparison studies found that wider grass margins had higher abundance of habitat-sensitive butterflies, macro-moths and micro-moths than narrower or conventional width margins (Action 3982). Two site comparison studies found that the species richness of butterflies was higher in longer or wider uncultivated margins than in shorter, narrower or conventional width margins (Action 3981). One site comparison study found that the abundance of butterflies in wide uncultivated margins was higher than in conventional margins (Action 3981).",
